<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a>: Okay, so I'm working on the God documentation when it finally dawns on me a very minor change could make a nice flavor addition for the game: <p>
Call all the God spellbooks something else, namely prayerbooks. IIRC, the oldtime Moria worked that way... 
</p>
<p>
The collection books wouldn't have to be renamed, as you would have "books" for the standard spells and "holy tomes" for the God spells. 
</p>
<p>
Of course, that opens up the can of worms of "praying" to a god vs. casting a "prayer", but I thought I'd mention it anyway. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a></strong>: That would imply that those spells work differently, though.  The prayer mechanics are different in Moria and Angband, but they aren't in ToME.  I think the name change would be misleading and harmful. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: It's been too long since I played Moria. I thought the mechanics were the same. Anyway, if you check the brandnew Doc/Intro to Gods, I've noted that "god spells" reference is preferable to "prayers" anyway, in order to prevent confusion... but thanks for the feedback. <img src="./wiki/starshine/img/smile.png" alt=":)" height="15" width="15"> 
</p>
<p>
Hey, while I'm at it, Neil, I wanted to ask you somehting. There's a certain "if you do X, God will abandon you forever" phrase...and I'm wondering whether that should remain in Doc or get axed as a spoiler. IMHO, it's a spoiler and should go. Input please? 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a></strong>: Good question.  I think you're right.  Remove it from the docs but make sure to add it to Galadriel's speech (not technically in the docs, but essentially mid-game spoily documentation). 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: I'll axe it from the Doc if you can put it on the to-do list for the code? 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a></strong>: I just added a note for each Vala in the speech conditional on which (if any) you are following. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: Great. It's out of the Doc...along with a few more references to Morgoth. It's amazing how those keep cropping up.  
</p>
